The comparison function will also generate a subdirectory called \texttt{compcodeR\_code}, where the R code used to perform each of the comparisons is detailed in HTML reports, and another subdirectory called \texttt{compcodeR\_figure}, where the plots generated in the comparison are saved. The code HTML reports can also be generated manually for a given result file (given that the \Robject{code} component is present in the \Robject{compData} object (see Section~\ref{sec:resultformat}), using the function \Rfunction{generateCodeHTMLs}. For example, to generate a report containing the code that was run to perform the t-test above, as well as the output from the \R{} console, we can write:
<<label = generatecode, echo = TRUE, eval = FALSE>>=
generateCodeHTMLs("B_625_625_5spc_repl1_ttest.rds", ".")
@
These reports are useful to check that there were no errors or warnings when running the differential expression analyses. 

\subsubsection{Direct command-line call}
Next, we show how to run the comparison by calling the function \Rfunction{runComparison} directly. In this case, we need to supply the function with a list of result files to use as a basis for the comparison. We can also provide a list of parameters (p-value thresholds, the differential expression methods to include in the comparison, etc.). The default values of these parameters are outlined in the reference manual. The following code provides an example, given the data generated above.
<<label = nogui-comparison, echo = TRUE, eval = FALSE, tidy = FALSE>>=
file.table <- data.frame(input.files = c("B_625_625_5spc_repl1_voom.limma.rds", 
                                         "B_625_625_5spc_repl1_ttest.rds", 
                                         "B_625_625_5spc_repl1_edgeR.exact.rds"), 
                         stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
parameters <- list(incl.nbr.samples = NULL, incl.replicates = NULL, 
                   incl.dataset = "B_625_625", incl.de.methods = NULL, 
                   fdr.threshold = 0.05, tpr.threshold = 0.05, 
                   typeI.threshold = 0.05, ma.threshold = 0.05, 
                   fdc.maxvar = 1500, overlap.threshold = 0.05, 
                   fracsign.threshold = 0.05, 
                   comparisons = c("auc", "fdr", "tpr", "ma", "correlation"))
runComparison(file.table = file.table, parameters = parameters, output.directory = ".")
@
By setting \Robject{incl.nbr.samples}, \Robject{incl.replicates} and \Robject{incl.de.methods} to \Robject{NULL}, we ask \Rpackage{compcodeR} to include all results provided in the \Robject{file.table}. By providing a vector of values for each of these variables, it is possible to limit the selection to a subset of the provided files. Please note that the values given to \Robject{incl.replicates} and \Robject{incl.nbr.samples} are matched with values of the \Rcode{info.parameters\$repl.id} and \Rcode{info.parameters\$samples.per.cond} slots in the data/result objects, and that the values given to \Robject{incl.de.methods} are matched with values stored in the \Rcode{method.names\$full.name} slot of the result objects. If the values do not match, the corresponding result object will not be considered in the comparison. Consult the package manual for the full list of comparison methods available for use with the \Rfunction{runComparison} function. Setting \Rfunction{parameters = NULL} implies that all results provided in the \Robject{file.table} are used, and that all parameter values are set to their defaults (see the reference manual). Note that only one dataset identifier can be provided to the comparison (that is, \Robject{parameters\$incl.dataset} must be a single string).


\section{Using your own data}
The \Rpackage{compcodeR} package provides a straightforward function for simulating count data (\Rfunction{generateSyntheticData}). However, it is easy to apply the interfaced differential expression methods to your own data, given that it is provided in a \Robject{compData} object (see Section~\ref{sec:dataformat} below for a description of the data format). You can use the function \Rfunction{check\_compData} to check that your object satisfies the necessary criteria to be fed into the differential expression methods. 

To create a \Robject{compData} object from a count matrix and a data frame with sample annotations, you can use the function \Rfunction{compData}. The following code provides a minimal example. Note that you need to provide a \Robject{dataset} name (a 'description' of the simulation settings) as well as a unique data set identifier \Robject{uID}, which has to be unique for each \Robject{compData} object (e.g., for each simulation instance, even if the same simulation parameters are used). 
<<create-compData, eval = TRUE, tidy = FALSE>>=
count.matrix <- matrix(round(1000*runif(4000)), 1000, 4)
sample.annot <- data.frame(condition = c(1, 1, 2, 2))
info.parameters <- list(dataset = "mytestdata", uID = "123456")
cpd <- compData(count.matrix = count.matrix, 
                sample.annotations = sample.annot, 
                info.parameters = info.parameters)
check_compData(cpd)
@

\section{Providing your own differential expression code}\label{sec:ownmethods}
The \Rpackage{compcodeR} package provides an interface for calling some of the most commonly used differential expression methods developed for RNAseq data. However, it is easy to incorporate your own favorite method. In principle, this can be done in one of two ways:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Write a \Rfunction{XXX.createRmd} function (where \Robject{XXX} corresponds to your method), similar to the ones provided in the package, which creates a \Robject{.Rmd} file containing the code that is run to perform the differential expression analysis. Then call this function through the \Rfunction{runDiffExp} function. When implementing your function, make sure that the output is a \Robject{compData} object, structured as described in Section~\ref{sec:resultformat}. The \Rfunction{*.createRmd} functions provided in the package take the following input arguments:
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{data.path} -- the path to the \Robject{.rds} file containing the \Robject{compData} object to which the differential expression will be applied.
\item \Robject{result.path} -- the path to the \Robject{.rds} file where the resulting \Robject{compData} object will be stored.
\item \Robject{codefile} -- the name of the code (with extension .Rmd) where the code will be stored.
\item any arguments for setting parameters of the differential expression analysis.
\end{itemize}

\item Run the differential expression analysis completely outside the \Rpackage{compcodeR} package, and save the result in a \Robject{compData} object with the slots described in Section~\ref{sec:resultformat}. 
\end{enumerate}

You can use the \Rfunction{check\_compData\_results} function to check if your object satisfies the necessary conditions for being used as the output of a differential expression analysis and compared to results obtained by other methods with \Rpackage{compcodeR}.

\section{The format of the data and result objects}
This section details the format of the data and result objects generated and used by the \Rpackage{compcodeR} package. Both objects are of the \Robject{compData} class. The format guidelines below must be be followed if you apply the functions in the package to a data set of your own, or to differential expression results generated outside the package. Note that for most of the functionality of the package, the objects should be saved separately to files with a \Robject{.rds} extension, and the path of this object is provided to the functions. 

\subsection{The data object}\label{sec:dataformat}
The \Robject{compData} data object used by \Rpackage{compcodeR} is an S4 object with the following slots:
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{count.matrix} [\Robject{class matrix}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- the count matrix, with rows representing genes and columns representing samples.
\item \Robject{sample.annotations} [\Robject{class data.frame}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- sample annotations. Each row corresponds to one sample, and each column to one annotation. The data objects generated by the \Rfunction{generateSyntheticData} function have two annotations:
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{condition} [\Robject{class character} or \Robject{numeric}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- the class for each sample. Currently the differential expression implementations in the package supports only two-group comparisons, hence the \Robject{condition} should have exactly two unique values.
\item \Robject{depth.factor} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the depth factor for each sample. This factor, multiplied by the \Robject{sequencing depth}, corresponds to the target library size of the sample when simulating the counts. 
\end{itemize}
\item \Robject{info.parameters} [\Robject{class list}] -- a list detailing the parameter values that have been used for the simulation. 
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{dataset} [\Robject{class character}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- the name of the data set.
\item \Robject{samples.per.cond} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of samples in each of the two conditions.
\item \Robject{n.diffexp} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of genes that are simulated to be differentially expressed between the two conditions.
\item \Robject{repl.id} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- a replicate number, which can be set to differentiate between different instances generated with the exact same simulation settings.
\item \Robject{seqdepth} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the "base" sequencing depth that was used for the simulations. For each sample, it is modified by multiplication with a value sampled uniformly between \Robject{minfact} and \Robject{maxfact} to generate the actual sequencing depth for the sample. 
\item \Robject{minfact} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the lower bound on the values used to multiply the \Robject{seqdepth} to generate the actual sequencing depth for the individual samples.  
\item \Robject{maxfact} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the upper bound on the values used to multiply the \Robject{seqdepth} to generate the actual sequencing depth for the individual samples.  
\item \Robject{fraction.upregulated} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the fraction of the differentially expressed genes that were simulated to be upregulated in condition 2 compared to condition 1. Must be in the interval [0, 1]. The remaining differentially expressed genes are simulated to be downregulated in condition 2.
\item \Robject{between.group.diffdisp} [\Robject{class logical}] -- whether the counts from the two conditions were simulated with different dispersion parameters.
\item \Robject{filter.threshold.total} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the filter threshold that is applied to the total count across all samples. All genes for which the total count is below this number have been excluded from the data set in the simulation process.
\item \Robject{filter.threshold.mediancpm} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the filter threshold that is applied to the median count per million (cpm) across all samples. All genes for which the median cpm is below this number have been excluded from the data set in the simulation process.
\item \Robject{fraction.non.overdispersed} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the fraction of the genes in the data set that are simulated according to a model without overdispersion (i.e., a Poisson model).
\item \Robject{random.outlier.high.prob} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the fraction of extremely high random outlier counts introduced in the simulated data sets. Please consult (Soneson \& Delorenzi 2013) for a detailed description of the different types of outliers. 
\item \Robject{random.outlier.low.prob} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the fraction of extremely low random outlier counts introduced in the simulated data sets. Please consult (Soneson \& Delorenzi 2013) for a detailed description of the different types of outliers. 
\item \Robject{single.outlier.high.prob} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the fraction of extremely high single outlier counts introduced in the simulated data sets. Please consult (Soneson \& Delorenzi 2013) for a detailed description of the different types of outliers. 
\item \Robject{single.outlier.low.prob} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the fraction of extremely low single outlier counts introduced in the simulated data sets. Please consult (Soneson \& Delorenzi 2013) for a detailed description of the different types of outliers. 
\item \Robject{effect.size} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the degree of differential expression, i.e., a measure of the minimal effect size. Alternatively, a vector of provided effect sizes for each of the variables. 
\item \Robject{uID} [\Robject{class character}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- a unique identification number given to each data set. For the data sets simulated with \Rpackage{compcodeR}, it consists of a sequence of 10 randomly generated alpha-numeric characters.
\end{itemize}
\item \Robject{filtering} [\Robject{class character}] -- a summary of the filtering that has been applied to the data.
\item \Robject{variable.annotations} [\Robject{class data.frame}] -- annotations for each of the variables in the data set. Each row corresponds to one variable, and each column to one annotation. No annotation is mandatory, however some of them are necessary if the differential expression results for the data are going to be used for certain comparison tasks. The data sets simulated within \Rpackage{compcodeR} have the following named variable annotations:
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{truedispersions.S1} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the true dispersions used in the simulations of the counts for the samples in condition 1.
\item \Robject{truedispersions.S2} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the true dispersions used in the simulations of the counts for the samples in condition 2.
\item \Robject{truemeans.S1} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the true mean values used in the simulations of the counts for the samples in condition 1.
\item \Robject{truemeans.S2} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the true mean values used in the simulations of the counts for the samples in condition 2.
\item \Robject{n.random.outliers.up.S1} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely high random outliers introduced for each gene in condition 1.
\item \Robject{n.random.outliers.up.S2} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely high random outliers introduced for each gene in condition 2.
\item \Robject{n.random.outliers.down.S1} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely low random outliers introduced for each gene in condition 1.
\item \Robject{n.random.outliers.down.S2} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely low random outliers introduced for each gene in condition 2.
\item \Robject{n.single.outliers.up.S1} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely high single outliers introduced for each gene in condition 1.
\item \Robject{n.single.outliers.up.S2} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely high single outliers introduced for each gene in condition 2.
\item \Robject{n.single.outliers.down.S1} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely low single outliers introduced for each gene in condition 1.
\item \Robject{n.single.outliers.down.S2} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the number of extremely low single outliers introduced for each gene in condition 2.
\item \Robject{M.value} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the estimated log2-fold change between conditions 1 and 2 for each gene. These values were estimated using the \Rpackage{edgeR} package.
\item \Robject{A.value} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the estimated average expression in conditions 1 and 2 for each gene. These values were estimated using the \Rpackage{edgeR} package.
\item \Robject{truelog2foldchanges} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the ``true'' log2-fold changes between conditions 1 and 2 for each gene, based on the parameters used for simulation.
\item \Robject{upregulation} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- a binary annotation (0/1) indicating which genes are simulated to be upregulated in condition 2 compared to condition 1. (Upregulated genes are indicated with a 1.)
\item \Robject{downregulation} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- a binary annotation (0/1) indicating which genes are simulated to be downregulated in condition 2 compared to condition 1. (Downregulated genes are indicated with a 1.)
\item \Robject{differential.expression} [\Robject{class numeric}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}} for many comparisons, such as the computation of false discovery rates, true positive rates, ROC curves, false discovery curves etc.)-- a binary annotation (0/1) indicating which genes are simulated to be differentially expressed in condition 2 compared to condition 1. In other words, the sum of \Robject{upregulation} and \Robject{downregulation}.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
To apply the functions of the package to a \Robject{compData} object of the type detailed above, it needs to be saved to a file with extension \Robject{.rds}. To save the object \Robject{cpd} to the file \Robject{saveddata.rds}, simply type 
<<label = savedata, echo = TRUE, eval = FALSE>>=
saveRDS(cpd, "saveddata.rds")
@

\subsection{The result object}\label{sec:resultformat}
When applying one of the differential expression methods interfaced through \Rpackage{compcodeR}, the \Robject{compData} object is extended with some additional slots. These are described below. 
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{analysis.date} [\Robject{class character}] -- the date and time when the differential expression analysis was performed.
\item \Robject{package.version} [\Robject{class character}] -- the version of the packages used in the differential expression analysis.
\item \Robject{method.names} [\Robject{class list}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- a list containing the names of the differential expression method, which should be used to identify the results in the comparison. Contains two components:
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{short.name} [\Robject{class character}] -- a short name, used for convenience.
\item \Robject{full.name} [\Robject{class character}] -- a fully identifying name of the differential expression method, including e.g. version numbers and parameter values. In the method comparisons, the results will be grouped based on the \Robject{full.name}.
\end{itemize}
\item \Robject{code} [\Robject{class character}] -- the code that was used to run the differential expression analysis, in R markdown (.Rmd) format.
\item \Robject{result.table} [\Robject{class data.frame}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- a data frame containing the results of the differential expression analysis. Each row corresponds to one gene, and each column to a value generated by the analysis. The precise columns will depend on the method applied. The following columns are used by at least one of the methods interfaced by \Rpackage{compcodeR}:
\begin{itemize}
\item \Robject{pvalue} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the nominal p-values.
\item \Robject{adjpvalue} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- p-values adjusted for multiple comparisons.
\item \Robject{logFC} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- estimated log-fold changes between the two conditions.
\item \Robject{score} [\Robject{class numeric}] ({\color{blue}{mandatory}}) -- the score that will be used to rank the genes in order of significance. Note that {\color{red}{high scores always signify differential expression, that is, a strong association with the predictor}}. For example, for methods returning a nominal p-value the score is generally obtained as \Robject{1 - pvalue}.
\item \Robject{FDR} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the false discovery rate estimate.
\item \Robject{posterior.DE} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the posterior probability of differential expression.
\item \Robject{prob.DE} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- The conditional probability of differential expression.
\item \Robject{lfdr} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- the local false discovery rate.
\item \Robject{statistic} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- a test statistic from the differential expression analysis.
\item \Robject{dispersion.S1} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- dispersion estimate in condition 1.
\item \Robject{dispersion.S2} [\Robject{class numeric}] -- dispersion estimate in condition 2.
\end{itemize}
For many of the comparison methods, the naming of the result columns is important. For example, the p-value column must be named \Robject{pvalue} in order to be recognized by the comparison method computing type I error. Similarly, either an \Robject{adjpvalue} or an \Robject{FDR} column must be present in order to apply the comparison methods requiring adjusted p-value/FDR cutoffs. If both are present, the \Robject{adjpvalue} column takes precedence over the \Robject{FDR} column. 
\end{itemize}

To be used in the comparison function, the result \Robject{compData} object must be saved to a \Robject{.rds} file. 

\section{The evaluation/comparison methods}\label{sec:compmethods}
This section provides an overview of the methods that are implemented in \Rpackage{compcodeR} for comparing differential expression results obtained by different methods. The selection of which methods to apply is made through a graphical user interface that is opened when the \Rfunction{runComparisonGUI} function is called (see Figure~\ref{fig:screenshot-gui}). Alternatively, the selection of methods can be supplied to the \Rfunction{runComparison} function directly, to circumvent the GUI. 

\subsection{ROC (one replicate/all replicates)}\label{sec:roc}
This method computes a ROC curve for either a single representative among the replicates of a given data set, or for all replicates (in separate plots). The ROC curves are generated by plotting the true positive rate (TPR, on the y-axis) versus the false positive rate (FPR, on the x-axis) when varying the cutoff on the \Robject{score} (see the description of the result object above). A good ranking method gives a ROC curve which passes close to the upper left corner of the plot, while a bad method gives a ROC curve closer to the diagonal. Calculation of the ROC curves requires that the differential expression status of each gene is provided (see the description of the data object in Section~\ref{sec:dataformat}). Figure~\ref{fig:roc} shows an example of ROC curves for a single replicate.

\begin{center}
\resizebox{140mm}{!}{\includegraphics[trim=0 0 170mm 0, clip = true]{compcodeR_figure/rocone-1.png}}%
\captionof{figure}{}\label{fig:roc}%
\end{center}

\subsection{AUC}\label{sec:auc}
This comparison method computes the area under the ROC curve (see section~\ref{sec:roc}) and represents the result in boxplots, where each box summarizes the results for one method across all replicates of a data set. A good ranking method gives to a large value of the AUC. This requires that the differential expression status of each gene is provided (see the description of the data object in Section~\ref{sec:dataformat}). Figure~\ref{fig:auc} shows an example.

